                        "libelle": "Analyse Numérique",
                        "imageRoot": "img/matrice.png",
                        "presentation": "<p class='qtext_para'>I know what it’s like not to enjoy life. And I know what it’s like to turn thirty, then eventually 33, the age Jesus was when he died and left this earth. But for me there was no end in sight. My grandparents were still alive in their late eighties. What I’m saying is that even with belief in an afterlife, you have to suffer an awfully long time in anguish for the afterlife to come. Only when I gave up on the afterlife and God did this life become worth living. And that made it worth everything. It’s the whole point. I’d never ever go back. I’m still only sixty. My parents lived till almost eighty and my grandparents into their nineties. I look forward to another couple decades of this wonderful life I finally discovered. If that’s all there is, I’m not sorry I found it.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Like an ice cream or other favourite food or great time. It lasts only so long but it’s sure worth it while it lasts.</p>0.",
                        "importance": "<p class='qtext_para'>This is a good question. What if there is no God, and there is no afterlife? Is there a reason to keep on living.</p><p class='qtext_para'>I will say yes, and I am not alone in saying yes. The Buddha was agnostic about divine beings and, himself, refused to present a theory of the afterlife, and refuted all existing theories about life after death.</p><p class='qtext_para'>What he did was that he learned how to enjoy life <i>regardless of external conditions.</i></p><p class='qtext_para'>What if the following is true? Each of us has the ability to, and is free to:</p><ul><li>Understand our actions and their consequences</li><li>Understand the nature and origins of suffering and suffer a great deal less</li><li>Understand the nature and origins of both confusion and clarity, choose clarity over confusion, and create clarity of thought, feelings, and body, and experience this as enjoyable</li><li>Understand the nature and origins of vitality, health, joy, and peace and cultivate these qualities</li><li>Create a life of creativity and/or service, and so be a unique gift to the world</li></ul><p class='qtext_para'>Even a chicken makes the most of her life. How about if we make the most of ours before we throw in the towel?</p>0.",
