                        "imageRoot": "img/aoo.png",
                        "presentation": "<p class='qtext_para'>The point of life is whatever you decide to make it. I’m an atheist and don’t believe in an afterlife, so I’m right here with you in this boat. The way I look at it, <b>you</b> give your life meaning. <b>You</b> define what makes life worth living.</p><blockquote><p class='qtext_para'>If you do not enjoy life then wouldn’t it be literally better if you killed yourself?</p></blockquote><p class='qtext_para'>Well…depends on how you define “better” and in what way you don’t enjoy life. If you don’t enjoy life because of a temporary situation or a situation that is reversible, like a temporary but painful illness, then it’s not strictly better (again, though, we haven’t exactly defined what “better” means) since the potential exists for you to regain your previous independence and continue doing what you love to do. If you don’t enjoy life because you’re stuck with a permanent illness that prevents you from doing what you enjoy and find fulfilling - that is, what gives your life meaning - then it might be rational to take your own life. But again, is it “better”? That’s unclear simply because I’m not sure how you’re defining “better”. And definitions matter when we’re talking about comparisons like this - what is the metric you are using to judge life, for example?</p>2.",
