                        "imageRoot": "img/project_management.png",
                        "presentation": "<p class='qtext_para'>Some will say there is God and some will say there isn't.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Let's say there isn't.</p><p class='qtext_para'>So, why your present should be influenced by a single fact that there isn't God and afterlife?</p><p class='qtext_para'>God or No God, one thing is for sure that you are made up of something (atom) and it gets converted into something else (atom again when you die)</p><p class='qtext_para'>One thing is for sure:</p><blockquote><p class='qtext_para'>What is created will be destroyed</p></blockquote><p class='qtext_para'>So, as a human the best thing you can do is to live in present.</p><p class='qtext_para'><b>Experience things and stay happy.</b></p><p class='qtext_para'>If you want to put some more effort then do something which will impact life of others (Human, Animal or Nature) and make it better.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Point is, you are dying and you are going to die and you can't do anything about it.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Make your journey pleasant for yourself and others.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Collect Memories and Experience thing. That the purpose of life and rule of living.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Good Luck!</p>5.",
                        "importance": "<div id='jilCWq'></div><span class='rendered_qtext'><p class='qtext_para'>Let’s start by turning the question around: if there <i>is</i> a god and an afterlife, then what is the point of (this) life? There are only three possibilities:</p><ul><li>You’re <i>sure</i> your afterlife will be better than this one — in which case you might as well end this one as soon as possible.</li><li>You’re sure it <i>won’t</i> be — so your main motive for remaining alive is to defer post-life suffering for as long as possible. That doesn’t sound like a very happy or pleasant way to live.</li><li>You’re not sure either way — in which case you <i>still</i> don’t know what to do, because there’s no reliable way to find out. If there are any gods, and they want us to do something in this life, then they certainly haven’t given us any clear indication of what that is.</li></ul><p class='qtext_para'>So simply postulating the existence of gods and an afterlife about which we know nothing doesn’t help to resolve your problem; it still means you have to work out yourself how you intend to live.</p><p class='qtext_para'>But of course most people go on living because they <i>like</i> it. If you don’t like it, and you don’t see any prospect of ever liking it, then you’re entitled to put an end to yourself, but people who do that are very much the exception, no matter what they believe. And we tend to believe that other human beings are special because we regard ourselves as special.</p><p class='qtext_para'>Here’s a tip; if your assumptions about people who don’t believe in your god lead you to conclude they should all act differently than they do, then your assumptions are probably wrong.</p><p class='qtext_para'><span class='qlink_container'><a href='https://jonjermey.quora.com/Jermeys-Rules-of-Theological-Debate' target='_blank'>Jermey's Rules of Theological Debate by Jon Jermey on Permanent stuff</a></span></p><p class='qtext_para'><i>5. If your religious beliefs require you to assume that millions of people are lying or misled about how they really feel, what they really think, or what they really do, you should expect to meet resistance to your claims.</i></p>5.",
